	abstract = {In virtual learning environments, pedagogical agents are often used to simulate the presence of an instructor. Traditionally, these agents deliver instructional content through narration, either alone or accompanied by a visual avatar. Recent advancements in large language models, such as GPT, have enabled the development of conversational agents that provide more responsive and interactive learner support. This study examined the impact of integrating GPT and a 3D avatar into conventional voice-guided instructional modules. A 2 (3D avatar: present vs. absent) × 2 (GPT chat: enabled vs. disabled) factorial experiment was conducted to evaluate their effects on the perceived social presence of the agent, engagement, and learning outcomes—measured by self-reported knowledge gain and quiz performance. Results from a preliminary study with 34 participants showed that GPT integration significantly enhanced social presence, perceived knowledge gain, and quiz scores. Although the agent’s avatar did not improve quiz performance, it led to higher perceived knowledge gain and social presence. These findings highlight both the individual and combined effects of GPT and avatars in virtual instructional environments. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
