	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/AIBThings66987.2025.11296253},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105031734852?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Recent years have seen a transformational educational environment due to the growing usage of artificial intelligence. It has evolved from a technological niche to a revolutionary solution that redefines teaching, learning and assessment. The motivation of this paper is to explore the capacities of small language models, which lack sufficient research in educational contexts, especially Phi-4. The main contribution of this study is to offer a benchmark of Phi-4 alongside a range of both small and large language models, such as Mistral, Falcon, Qwen and DeepSeek, across various school subjects. The goal is to evaluate differences in performance, adaptability, and potential integration into educational environments. In the pursuit of developing a comprehensive benchmark for Phi-4 in education, the methodology is characterized by the building of a custom dataset with question and answer pairs covering different subjects to allow an evaluation of different small and large language models. When evaluating the models with a ROUGE score for all subjects combined, it shows that Phi- 3.5 -mini-instruct leads in recall for ROUGE-1 and ROUGE-L and Falcon-7b-instruct shows the best score regarding the precision and F1 score across both ROUGE-1 and ROUGE-L as well as speed. Phi-4-mini-instruct reaches the second best score for all metrics except precision and F1 score for ROUGE-L where it ended in third place. Regarding the evaluation per subject, Falcon-7b-instruct gets the best scores for geography, medical and science. Phi-3-medium-128k-instruct gets the best score for math. Despite some limitations in the size of the custom dataset and number of subjects evaluated, this study can provide educators, researchers, and policymakers with insights into the strengths and limitations of emerging AI technologies. It can also lay the groundwork for a more inclusive understanding of AI in education, since the AI revolution will reshape how knowledge is communicated and acquired in the coming years.  © 2025 IEEE.},
