	doi = {10.1109/FIE63693.2025.11328512},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033036304?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {This Full research paper describes programming practices used by students in a computer science (CS) program. Debugging is a vital aspect of programming, yet it is often an overlooked skill in CS education. While novice programmers frequently encounter errors, they often lack formal, explicit instructions in debugging strategies, leaving them to rely on trial-and-error methods and learning through experience. This gap is especially problematic in courses that use automated grading systems, where students must independently identify and resolve issues in their written program. This study presents a qualitative investigation into how undergraduate CS students acquire debugging strategies independently through practice in project-based learning environments. Through semi-structured interviews with CS majors, we examine students' self-directed debugging practices, resource utilization, and the cognitive and emotional challenges they encounter. The study findings indicate that students often feel ill-equipped to debug effectively, leading to frustration and inefficient problemsolving. Thematic analysis of the student responses to the interviews reveals that students predominantly rely on early-learned, unsystematic methods, such as print statements, online searches, and AI-assisted tools, often leading to inefficient debugging and prolonged frustration. Access to knowledgeable peers in social circles is uneven, introducing disparities in learning outcomes. Findings suggest that students tend to anchor to the first debugging strategies they encounter regardless of their efficacy and rarely develop a principled approach to fault localization or hypothesis-driven debugging. These results underscore the need for more empirical studies on debugging practices in instruction, as well as research on pedagogical interventions that foreground debugging as a core learning objective. This study identifies patterns that motivate the need for the integration of explicit debugging instruction, including diagnostic reasoning and code comprehension techniques, into early-stage CS education to foster more robust problem-solving capabilities and reduce reliance on ad hoc methods. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {debugging; programming; qualitative analysis; Software engineering; Thematic analysis},
